I'm not sure what you mean by "file syntax" - it's not even totally
consistent within UNIX systems.  Berkeley allows up to 255 chars
between slashes, System V only counts the first 14, and V9 returns
errors for more than 14.  However, the basic notion of /a/b/c or ..
or c/d, with distinct upper/lower case, is the same.  I don't have
a POSIX spec handy, but I am not sure POSIX addresses filenames
other than for /usr/include purposes.

If you're concerned about filesystem semantics, there are variations
there, too, especially when you take RFS and NFS into account.
They are mostly pretty subtle, involving locking or keeping a file
open after it's unlinked.

	Mark

